Short answer is: because the lambda class is hidden ([JEP 371 in JDK15][1] standardized it and exposed an API, but it&#39;s been present since JDK 7) and cannot be accessed by other classes. You can find more information in blogposts and articles like [this one][2].

---

If we define:
```java
public static Runnable lambdaTest() {
    return () -&gt; {
    };
}

public static Runnable anonymTest() {
    return new Runnable() {
        @Override
        public void run() {
        }
    };
}
```
and run:
```java
System.out.println(Main.class.isHidden());
System.out.println(anonymTest().getClass().isHidden());
System.out.println(lambdaTest().getClass().isHidden());
```
we&#39;ll get:
```bash
false
false
true
```

---

If we print the name of the lambda class, we&#39;ll get different results on different JDK, but both boiling down to the same concept:
```
JDK 8-10: java.lang.ClassNotFoundException: Main$$Lambda$1/791452441
JDK 11+:  java.lang.ClassNotFoundException: Main$$Lambda$1/0x0000000800060840
```

[Class#getName() JavaDoc][3] says:

&gt; If the class or interface is hidden, then the result is a string of the form: N + &#39;/&#39; + \&lt;suffix&gt; where N is the binary name indicated by the class file passed to Lookup::defineHiddenClass, and &lt;suffix&gt; is an unqualified name.

If you wanted to see the implementation: native JDK code for JDK 9 [can be found here][4] ([here&#39;s a short description of mirror classes][5]) and [here&#39;s the JDK 18 code][6] (been there since 15). If you want to read more, I recommend [this SO answer][7].

---

Finally let&#39;s see the `ClassLoader` code that looks up the class for loading:
```java
protected final Class&lt;?&gt; findLoadedClass(String name) {
    if (!checkName(name))
        return null;
    return findLoadedClass0(name);
}

// true if the name is null or has the potential to be a valid binary name
private static boolean checkName(String name) {
    if ((name == null) || (name.isEmpty()))
        return true;
    if ((name.indexOf(&#39;/&#39;) != -1) || (name.charAt(0) == &#39;[&#39;))
        return false;
    return true;
}
```

If the class name contains a `/` char, it&#39;s resolved as not a valid binary name and cannot be loaded. If you wondered about the `[` char - it marks an array class.


  [1]: https://openjdk.org/jeps/371
  [2]: https://foojay.io/today/what-are-hidden-classes-in-java-15/
  [3]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/15/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/Class.html#getName()
  [4]: https://github.com/AdoptOpenJDK/openjdk-jdk9/blob/f00b63d24697cce8067f468fe6cd8510374a46f5/hotspot/src/share/vm/oops/klass.cpp#L575-L586
  [5]: https://programming.vip/docs/diagram-class-loading.html
  [6]: https://github.com/openjdk/jdk18/blob/jdk-18+37/src/hotspot/share/classfile/classFileParser.cpp#L5920-L5938
  [7]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/72738837/in-java-what-does-the-i-e-forward-slash-mean-in-object-references-like-l

