Here is an example that shows you how to add a countdown [timer][1] to a `listview` :

**Step 1**: setup your `listview`:


    //data
    List&lt;String&gt; values = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    values.add(&quot;Item 1&quot;);
    values.add(&quot;Item 2&quot;);
    values.add(&quot;Item 3&quot;);


    ArrayAdapter&lt;String&gt; adapter = new ArrayAdapter&lt;&gt;(this, android.R.layout.simple_list_item_1, values);

    ListView recyclerView = findViewById(R.id.listView);

    recyclerView.setAdapter(adapter);

**step 2**: create a countdown `timer`:

    Timer timer = new Timer();
    TimerTask task = new TimerTask() {
        @Override
        public void run() {
            //do something in here
        }
    };

**step 3**: start your `timer`:

You have different option in here,

You can execute your code after the specified delay:

    //here your code will be execute after 5000 ms (5s)
    timer.schedule(task, 5000);

Schedules the specified task for repeated fixed-delay execution :

    //execute task every 5000 ms
    timer.scheduleAtFixedRate(task, 0, 5000);

**step 4**: connect the timer to our `listview` by adding our code in the `run` method:

        TimerTask task = new TimerTask() {
            @Override
            public void run() {
                recyclerView.post(new Runnable() {
                    @Override
                    public void run() {
                        adapter.add(&quot;New Item&quot;);
                    }
                });
            }
        };

Here we have to wrap our code inside `recyclerView.post()` because we are in a different `thread` and we can&#39;t touch the android `view` from it, we have to so `post` our `task` to the main `thread`

**Summary**: Here&#39;s what you might need to use:

    public class MainActivity extends AppCompatActivity {
    
        @Override
        protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {
            super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
            setContentView(R.layout.activity_main);
    
            //data
            List&lt;String&gt; values = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
            values.add(&quot;Item 1&quot;);
            values.add(&quot;Item 2&quot;);
            values.add(&quot;Item 3&quot;);
    
            ArrayAdapter&lt;String&gt; adapter = new ArrayAdapter&lt;&gt;(this, android.R.layout.simple_list_item_1, values);
    
            ListView recyclerView = findViewById(R.id.listView);
    
            recyclerView.setAdapter(adapter);
    
            Timer timer = new Timer();
            TimerTask task = new TimerTask() {
                @Override
                public void run() {
                    recyclerView.post(new Runnable() {
                        @Override
                        public void run() {
                            adapter.add(&quot;New Item&quot;);
                        }
                    });
                }
            };
            
            //here your code will be execute afer 5000 ms (5s)
            timer.schedule(task, 5000);
        }
    }


  [1]: https://developer.android.com/reference/java/util/Timer

The problem is the password encoder. It is required to build the auto-configured `UserDetailsService` that you inject in the contructor of the class.

You can break the cycle by making the bean factory method `static`:

    @Bean
    public static BCryptPasswordEncoder bcryptPasswordEncoder() {
        return new BCryptPasswordEncoder();
    }

You can also move the factory method to different configuration class. But in my opinion, your `WebSecurityConfig` is the canonical place for the method.

